body:
Hi!

This is just a question to clarify a behavior. Am I correct to assume that using new Hooks API would enable developers to create essentially memoized selectors by making a custom memoized hook that would read given values from reducer?

Something which very vaguely would be like this:

```javascript
// Defining a custom Hook for mapping values from reducer in any combination
// necessary. getTodos is just a simple wrapper for:
// state => state.main.todos
// while getEmojis is another pointing to another reducer state:
const useFromReducer = ([ state, dispatch ]) => useMemo(
  () => {
    const emojis = getEmojis(state);
    const todos = getTodos(state).map(
      (v, i) => ({ 
        ...v, 
        text: `${v.text} ${emojis[i % 3]}` 
      }));
    
    return {
      todos,
      dispatch
    };
  }, [ getEmojis(state), getTodos(state) ]);

// Then used in pure component like this:
const { todos, dispatch } = useFromReducer(useReducer(
  rootReducer,
  rootReducerInitialState, 
  mainActions.resetTodos));
```

So doesn't that essentially mean if I wish to get any combination of data from different reducers like for example could be done in "Reselect", I could create a it's logic inside the hook from multiple different reducers, and just pass it as a Custom Hook to the using component? Am I completely off the base if I sense this could make it able to create Reselect like memoized selectors by hand with hooks? That would be seriously awesome! ðŸ˜„
